          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 16px;">
           <p style=3D"margin: 0; color: #000000; font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Happy Sunday evening and welco=
me back to Dry Powder, I=E2=80=99m <b>Bill</b> <b>Cohan</b>. <br/><br/>Holl=
ywood has a problem. Finally, the streaming businesses at Disney, WBD, and =
Paramount Global are achieving profitability, with NBCU not far behind. But=
 the traditional TV networks that helped offset years of losses are all get=
ting smaller. Sure, they still throw off gobs of cash, but there=E2=80=99s =
nothing that Wall Street hates more than a declining asset. Everyone from <=
b>Bob Iger</b> to <b>Mike Cavanagh</b> has begun talking openly about <i>wh=
en</i> not <i>if</i> many of these legacy properties are moved off the bala=
nce sheet. But who=E2=80=99s the buyer?<br/><br/>More and more, I=E2=80=99m=
 hearing executives discussing private equity as a solution to the industry=
=E2=80=99s problem=E2=80=94and looking at the TPG-DirecTV deal as a model t=
o unlock value for investors. More on that, below the
fold.<br/><br/><i>But first=E2=80=A6</i><br/></p>
          </td>
