argin:0;color:#000000;font-size:16px;line-height:30px;margin-top:0;margin-b=
ottom:0;list-style-type:square;mso-special-format:bullet"><li><i>Trump=E2=
=80=99s Southampton vs. mid-island Treasury candidates</i>: <b>Donald Trump=
</b>=E2=80=99s blitz of cabinet picks has a conspicuous hole on the economi=
c front. Left unfilled are the treasury secretary, national economic adviso=
r, and chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, among other regu=
latory agencies that Wall Street and crypto types care a lot about. Assumin=
g Trump hasn=E2=80=99t made his Treasury pick by the time you read this, th=
e Wall Street consensus is forming around hedge fund manager <b>Scott Besse=
nt</b> over <b>Howard Lutnick</b>, the Cantor Fitzgerald C.E.O., who is als=
o leading Trump=E2=80=99s transition team=E2=80=94if indeed these are the t=
wo finalists for the job, now that <b>John
Paulson</b>, <b>Jamie Dimon</b>, <b>Gary Cohn</b>, and <b>Steve Schwarzman<=
/b> seem to be out of the running. (Over the weekend, <i>The Wall Street Jo=
urnal</i> started pushing Apollo C.E.O. <b>Marc</b> <b>Rowan</b>, one of th=
e subjects of my forthcoming book about the firm. Rowan, who is friendly wi=
th <b>Jared</b> <b>Kushner</b>, had considered going to Washington during T=
rump I, but that was before he took over Apollo in March 2021. I could see =
him as head of O.M.B., although I=E2=80=99m not sure if he=E2=80=99s ready =
to leave Apollo right now, as he=E2=80=99s still in the process of implemen=
ting his vision for the firm.)<br/><br/><b>Kyle Bass</b>, the outspoken hed=
ge fund manager, likes Bessent, at least partially on the grounds that the =
market likes Bessent. =E2=80=9CU.S. markets initially rallied on Trump=E2=
=80=99s win,=E2=80=9D he wrote Saturday on Twitter/X. =E2=80=9CThe moment H=
oward Lutnick decided he wanted the job, the markets sold off. The markets =
are telling Trump that Bessent is certainly the choice for
the position.=E2=80=9D Bessent =E2=80=9Cunderstands markets, economics, peo=
ple, and geopolitics better than anyone I=E2=80=99ve ever interacted with,=
=E2=80=9D Bass added. <br/><br/>That was quite an endorsement for Bessent, =
who once worked for <b>George Soros</b>. Hedge fund manager <b>Stanley</b> =
<b>Druckenmiller</b> likes Bessent, too. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s the only guy=
 I know who=E2=80=99s not only a market participant but very fluent and com=
fortable in academic circles,=E2=80=9D he told Axios. Meanwhile, in dissent=
, <b>Elon Musk</b>, Trump=E2=80=99s newly appointed DOGE co-leader, respond=
ed to Bass=E2=80=99s tweet with his view that =E2=80=9CBessent is a busines=
s-as-usual choice, whereas Howard Lutnick will actually enact change. Busin=
ess-as-usual is driving America bankrupt, so we need change one way or anot=
her.=E2=80=9D (Where does Elon come up with this logic?)<br/><br/><b>Jeffre=
y Sonnenfeld</b>, professor of management practice at the Yale School of Ma=
nagement, weighed in with a concise, unequivocal email: =E2=80=9CBessent wo=
uld be infinitely
better than Lutnick.=E2=80=9D Sonnenfeld is a straight shooter, but perhaps=
 he=E2=80=99s biased toward a fellow Yalie. Bessent is a 1984 Yale grad and=
 was president of one of its secret societies, Wolf=E2=80=99s Head. (Small =
world: He also worked for the legendary investor <b>Jim Rogers</b>, my prof=
essor at Columbia Business School.)<br/><br/>While conducting my unofficial=
 field research, I found mixed views among Wall Street executives, one of w=
hom texted me support for Team Lutnick on the grounds that the Cantor Fitzg=
erald C.E.O. had stronger management experience=E2=80=94not least of which =
is having brought the company back from the brink after 658 of its employee=
s perished in the September 11 attacks. (Though neither candidate, this per=
son texted, had =E2=80=9Cany idea=E2=80=9D what to do with tax policy.) Oth=
ers had memories of =E2=80=9Cwild=E2=80=9D Lutnick behavior during summers =
in the Hamptons and, of course, were less than complimentary about how Lutn=
ick treated the families of Cantor=E2=80=99s 9/11 victims, as has
been well documented. Another executive argued that, sure, Lutnick understa=
nds Wall Street=E2=80=99s plumbing, but people who have worked with him fin=
d him to be, and I quote, =E2=80=9Ca bit of a prick.=E2=80=9D Bessent comes=
 off as more polished, this person said, given both his training with Soros=
 and the Brown Brothers Harriman line on his r=C3=A9sum=C3=A9. =E2=80=9CHe=
=E2=80=99s more Southampton versus mid-island,=E2=80=9D this fellow wrote.<=
/li></ul></td>
