         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s3">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Just in time, a tem=
plate for how to deal with this chronic problem is emerging. While there ar=
e still options=E2=80=94an outright sale of the assets, bundling them into =
an I.P.O. or spinning them off to existing shareholders=E2=80=94the better =
choice may be to find a trusted partner in the private equity world who wil=
l buy a big stake in these wasting assets, find ways to run them better (or=
 just more profitably) than the big conglomerates have been able to, and ma=
ke everyone involved more money. <br/><br/>I keep hearing Hollywood executi=
ves reference the 2021 deal between AT&amp;T and TPG, the publicly traded a=
lternative asset behemoth, for DirecTV. You will recall that AT&amp;T agree=
d to buy DirecTV in 2014 for a whopping $67 billion, a price that stunned W=
all Street. The deal was a <b>John Stankey</b> special, as was the 2018 acq=
uisition of Time Warner for more than
$100 billion. Both deals were considered disasters, but neither stalled Sta=
nkey=E2=80=99s rise. He was named AT&amp;T C.E.O. in July 2020 and remains =
in charge today.<br/><br/>While Stankey proved to be a lousy acquirer of co=
mpanies, he=E2=80=99s actually turned out to be a pretty clever seller of t=
he dogs he bought. In April 2022, he unloaded the renamed WarnerMedia to Za=
z=E2=80=99s Discovery Communications in a Reverse Morris Trust deal, where =
AT&amp;T would own 71 percent of the new Warner Bros. Discovery. Zaz, an ol=
d-school cable TV guy who earned his stripes at NBC back when <b>Jack</b> <=
b>Welch</b>=E2=80=99s GE still owned it, eagerly took on Warners=E2=80=99 d=
eclining linear TV assets <i>plus</i> $55 billion of AT&amp;T=E2=80=99s mor=
e than <i>$180 billion </i>of debt.<br/><br/>The other smart thing Stankey =
did was begin the process of offloading DirecTV to TPG. <b>John Malone</b>,=
 Zaz=E2=80=99s longtime mentor and the acknowledged dean of the media busin=
ess, once owned a big chunk of DirecTV and sold it before things got
really bad. After AT&amp;T bought DirecTV, he used to tell people that the =
phone company could =E2=80=9Csell it now=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Csell it later=
, for less.=E2=80=9D AT&amp;T waited until 2021 to begin the process of sel=
ling DirecTV, choosing the wait-and-see strategy and then having little cho=
ice but to sell it for much less than the $67 billion it paid=E2=80=94provi=
ng Malone right, no surprise. <br/><br/>The first step in the deal was to s=
ell TPG a 30 percent stake in DirecTV for $1.6 billion in cash=E2=80=94a tr=
ansaction that, along with the debt on the company plus AT&amp;T and TPG pr=
eferred stock, valued DirecTV at only $16.25 billion, a far cry from $67 bi=
llion. (At the time, DirecTV had about $6.5 billion of EBITDA=E2=80=94and y=
es, it was declining=E2=80=94meaning TPG paid about 2.5x EBITDA.) By reduci=
ng its stake in DirecTV to 70 percent, AT&amp;T could deconsolidate the com=
pany from its financial statements and no longer had to report the business=
=E2=80=99s slow but steady decline or answer Wall Street=E2=80=99s question=
s about
subscriber losses. (Full disclosure: TPG is an investor in Puck.)<br/></td>
         </tr>
